ces class and racial hierarchies and diverts resources that could better support marginalized youth’s efforts to reach their educational and occupational goals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aAfrican American studentsxEducationvCase studies. 0aHispanic American studentsxEducationvCase studies. 0aPoor youthzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aPovertyzUnited States. 0aUrban youthzUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aacademics.  ablack youth.  abrown youth.  acareer.  aclass hierarchy.  adanger.  adrug use.  afamily life.  agangs.  ahomelessness.  ahunger.  aillness.  anonprofit organizations.  apeople of color.  apolicy makers.  apoverty cycle.  apoverty.  arace hierarchy.  arisk.  arisky behaviors.  aschool.  aservice class.  asocial hierarchy.  asocial issues.  asocial studies.  ateen parenthood.  ateen parents.  ateen.  ateenagers.  ateens.  aviolence.  awork life balance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978052029206240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965614423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965614/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles